# Visitor Face Verification + Memory Management

## Background

The current face verification system only supports **employees** — it looks up an employee by name, finds their stored photo, and runs DeepFace to compare. We now need to extend this to **visitors** and add guardrails so photos/captures don't fill up disk or memory over time.

### Key Observations from Research

| What | Current State |
|---|---|
| `Visitor` model | Already has `id_photo_path = Column(String)` — ready to use |
| `get_or_create_visitor()` | Reuses existing visitor profiles — a returning "John Smith" maps to the same row |
| `CAPTURES_DIR` | Saves **every** live capture with no cleanup — will fill disk over time |
| DeepFace model | Loaded once at warmup, shared across all calls — no per-request memory issue |
| Temp files | Cleaned up in `finally` block ✓ |

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Visitor Photo Lifecycle**: When a visitor first arrives, we have no stored photo to compare against. Two options:
> - **Option A (Recommended)**: On first visit, capture and save their face as `id_photo_path`. On subsequent visits, compare the live frame against that stored photo. This gives us cross-visit identity tracking.
> - **Option B**: Only compare within a single session (e.g., capture at name-giving, compare at check-out). No persistence.
>
> The plan below assumes **Option A**.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Capture Retention**: How long should diagnostic captures (the `CAPTURES_DIR` images) be kept?
> - Default in the plan: **7 days**, configurable via `CAPTURE_RETENTION_DAYS` env var.
> - Set to `0` to disable capture saving entirely.

